TY  - JOUR
T1  - “A” Business by Any Other Name: Firm Name Choice as a Signal of Firm Quality
AU  - McDevitt, Ryan C.
Y1  - 2014/08/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/676333
DO  - 10.1086/676333
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 909
EP  - 944
VL  - 122
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper considers when a firm?s deliberately chosen name can signal meaningful information. The average plumbing firm whose name begins with A or a number receives five times more service complaints than other firms and also charges higher prices. Relatedly, plumbers with A names advertise more in the Yellow Pages and on Google, and doing so is positively correlated with receiving complaints. As the use of A names is more prevalent in larger markets, I reconcile these findings with a simple model in which firms have different qualities and consumers have heterogeneous search costs.
AB  - This paper considers when a firm?s deliberately chosen name can signal meaningful information. The average plumbing firm whose name begins with A or a number receives five times more service complaints than other firms and also charges higher prices. Relatedly, plumbers with A names advertise more in the Yellow Pages and on Google, and doing so is positively correlated with receiving complaints. As the use of A names is more prevalent in larger markets, I reconcile these findings with a simple model in which firms have different qualities and consumers have heterogeneous search costs.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/676333
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/676333
Y2  - 2024/03/20
